  "nursesNote": "The nurse distinguishes three postpartum mood states. Baby blues are mild mood swings and tearfulness starting days 2-3 that resolve within about two weeks and need only support and reassurance. Postpartum depression is deeper and lasts more than two weeks, with sadness, guilt, and trouble caring for self or baby; it needs treatment (therapy and often SSRIs) and bonding is assessed. Postpartum psychosis is rare but a psychiatric emergency, with delusions or hallucinations and a real risk of harm to the mother or infant, so the mother is never left alone with the baby and usually needs hospitalization. The nurse screens mood, asks directly about thoughts of self-harm or harming the baby, ensures safety, and refers for treatment.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Screen postpartum mood and ask about self-harm or harm to the baby",
    "Distinguish baby blues from depression and psychosis",
    "Treat postpartum depression with therapy and medication as ordered",
    "Treat postpartum psychosis as an emergency; do not leave alone with the infant",
    "Provide support, rest, and follow-up"
  ],
